      <h2 class="title">
      <a href="/node/3623" title="This Week in Spring - August 7th, 2012">This Week in Spring - August 7th, 2012</a>
    </h2>
  
  
      <div class="meta">
              <div class="submitted">
          Submitted by Josh Long on Tue, 2012-08-07 14:38        </div>
      
              <div class="terms terms-inline"> in <ul class="links inline"><li class="taxonomy_term_14 first last"><a href="/taxonomy/term/14" rel="tag" title="">This Week in Spring</a></li>
</ul></div>
          </div>
  
  <div class="content">
     <P> 
 Welcome to another installment of <EM>This Week in Spring</EM>! 
 As usual, we've got a lot to cover, so let's get to it! 
</P>
<OL>
 	<li> I did a brief review of Manning's new book, 
	<a href = "http://www.springsource.org/node/3622">
	<EM>Spring Roo in Action</Em></a>. Check it, and the book, out!

	</li>
	  <LI> The <a href = "http://bit.ly/QWSrml">Cloud Foundry Integration for Eclipse Now Supports Tunneling to Services</a>. This increases the parity betwen the Eclipse support (and the SpringSource Tool Suite support)  and the <CODE>vmc</CODE> command-line client.  </LI>
		

		<LI> The VMware has a very cool blog taking a look the roles Spring and RabbitMQ play in 
			 <a href = "http://blogs.vmware.com/vfabric/2012/07/spring-and-rabbitmq-behind-indias-12-billion-person-biometric-database-1.html">in the new project behind India's 1.2 Billion Person Biometric Database</a>. <EM>Very</EM> cool! 
</LI>

<LI> David Turanski has a nice post that introduces a finer point of the Spring Data repository implementations: <a href ="http://blog.springsource.org/2012/08/03/the-most-amazing-java-type-declaration-ever/">its <EM>really</EM> elegant code-base!</A>   </LI> 


	  <LI> Jerry Kuch, a staff engineer at VMWare, did a very nice video <a href = "http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WCRyNesk_ak&feature=em-uploademail">on the new features in RabbitMQ</A></LI>
